To implement a queue using a stack:
1. We have to take two stacks. In the first stack, we have to push all the elements.
2. We will pop all the elements from the first stack and push them to the second stack.
3. Till the second stack is empty, we will pop all the elements from the second stack.
This is how we print a queue using a stack.

import java.util.*;

class Main{
    public static void main(String args[]){
        int arr[] = {1,2,3,4,5,6,7};

       Stack<Integer> s1 = new Stack<>();
       Stack<Integer>s2 = new Stack<>();

       for(int a:arr){
        s1.push(a);
       }
       while(!s1.isEmpty()){
        s2.push(s1.pop());
       }
       while (!s2.isEmpty()) {
        System.out.print(s2.pop()+" ");
        
       }


        }


}



To implement a queue using a single  stack, we use stack + recursion.
 static int dequeue(Stack<Integer> stack) {
        int top = stack.pop();

        if (stack.isEmpty()) {
            return top;
        }

        int result = dequeue(stack);
        stack.push(top);
        return result;
    }   



To implement a stack using a queue. Generally, in a queue we can access elements from the front and back, 
which means rear, but basically in a queue there is no option called rear. There is only the poll and peek.
That's it. We do not have access to the rear one, but to access that we use a double-ended queue (dq).
What are the methods we have? By using peek first and peek last, we can access the first and the last elements 
of the stack using the dq double-ended queue to implement a stack using a queue. 

In a Queue (FIFO)
You can normally:

Insert at the rear (back) → offer() / add()
Remove from the front → poll() / remove()
Peek at the front → peek()

If you need both front and rear
Use a Deque (Double Ended Queue):

Deque<Integer> dq = new LinkedList<>();

dq.offerLast(10);
dq.offerLast(20);
dq.offerLast(30);

System.out.println(dq.peekFirst()); // 10
System.out.println(dq.peekLast());  // 30
